<blue>1</blue>Kurt S. Adler , who helped change the look of Christmas décor as a major importer of handcrafted ornaments and convincing artificial trees , died on Nov. 25 at his home in Manhattan . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 83 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was heart failure , said his son Clifford . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Adler also had Parkinson 's disease . <br><blue>5</blue>Mr. Adler , whose products are often sold under the brand name Santa 's World , helped restore a European sensibility to Christmas decorations after World War II , when glass balls and other adornments from Germany were boycotted . <br><blue>6</blue>A Jewish refugee from Hitler 's Germany who did not celebrate Christmas , Mr. Adler recognized the holiday 's commercial potential after importing hand-carved angels from his native Bavaria . <br><blue>7</blue>He began providing American retailers with elaborate European snow globes and figurines that often became collectibles . <br><blue>8</blue>In the 1950 's , he began selling artificial trees from Nuremberg that looked so real a fire marshal demanded that he remove them from his Broadway showroom . <br><blue>9</blue>In the late 1960 's , he was among the first to sell strands of miniature lights from Italy . <br><blue>10</blue>He later helped start a trend by featuring images licensed from Walt Disney , Warner Brothers and even the Vatican Library . <br><blue>11</blue>Now run by his four children , his company , Kurt S. Adler Inc. / Santa 's World , offers more than 20,000 knickknacks for Christmas , Halloween , Easter , Thanksgiving and , most recently , Hanukkah . <br><blue>12</blue>Kurt Stephan Adler was born June 19 , 1921 , in Würzburg , Germany , and moved to Manhattan when he was 13 . <br><blue>13</blue>After serving in the United States Army during World War II , he drew on his experience as a shipping clerk to begin importing and exporting a hodgepodge of products like pottery , pineapples and glassware . <br><blue>14</blue>In addition to his son Clifford , of Scarsdale , N.Y. , Mr. Adler is survived by his wife , Marianne ; two sons , Howard , of Scarsdale , and Richard , of Manhattan ; one daughter , Karen , of Manhattan ; a sister , Hilda Schwartz , of Fort Lee , N.J. ; and nine grandchildren . <br><blue>15</blue>Mr. Adler 's first wife , Beatrice , died in 1992 . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>Germany</m_str> (5_37) 	<m_str>Hitler 's Germany who did not celebrate Christmas , Mr. Adler</m_str> (6_5) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>them</m_str> (8_24) 	<m_str>artificial trees</m_str> (8_9) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>World War II</m_str> (5_26) 	<m_str>World War II</m_str> (13_9) 	<br><blue>4(3)</blue>: <m_str>Manhattan</m_str> (14_35) 	<m_str>Manhattan</m_str> (1_33) 	<m_str>Manhattan</m_str> (14_43) 	<br><blue>5(17)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (14_18) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_21) 	<m_str>Mr. Adler 's</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Adler</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_13) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (13_16) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_30) 	<m_str>Kurt Stephan Adler</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_4) 	<m_str>Clifford , of Scarsdale , N.Y. , Mr. Adler</m_str> (14_6) 	<m_str>Mr. Adler</m_str> (6_14) 	<m_str>Mr. Adler , whose products are often sold under the brand name Santa 's World</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_8) 	<m_str>his son</m_str> (3_8) 	<m_str>Scarsdale , N.Y. , Mr. Adler</m_str> (14_9) 	<m_str>Clifford</m_str> (3_10) 	<br><blue>6(10)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (9_7) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (6_27) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_26) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_8) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (7_1) 	<m_str>A Jewish refugee from Hitler 's Germany who did not celebrate Christmas , Mr. Adler</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (8_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (8_22) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_4) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
